<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-441-215  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 441 215.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 14 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Western Union struck, replaces union workers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Western Union Corp. (strikes).andO;Ticker:    WU.andO;Topic:     Communications Workers of AmericaTelegraph SystemsStrikeFirings.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>WESTERN UNION STRUCK, REPLACES UNION WORKERS UPPER SADDLE RIVER, NEW JERSEY,U.S.A., 1990 AUGUST 14 (NB) -- Western Union, which is fighting for itsfinancial life and announced the sale of its profitable Easylink operationsto ATandamp;T, suffered a strike by members of the Communications Workers ofAmerica at its central telephone bureaus, computer centers and otheroperating facilities.andP;  In reply, the company replaced the union withtemporary workers but will continue to negotiate.andM;Western Union is continuing its regular operations, and all of its servicesare available to its customers on a normal basis.andM;Two-year contracts expired at midnight on August 6 but management and unionnegotiators continued to meet.andP;  On August 8, management proposed a 90-dayextension of the old contracts, but the unions rejected that proposal.andP;  Inaddition to wages, the principal contract issues include the extent of thecompany's rights to use outside contractors, employment of part-time workers,the level of employer/employee cost sharing in the provision of medicalinsurance, and various job-classification and other proposed productivityimprovements.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900813/Press Contact: Warren R. Bechtel, Western Union,201-818-5790)</TEXT></DOC>